VARIABLE ATTRIBUTES 
----------------------
 ğŸ”¸ Variable attributes are used instead of explicitly specifying a data type when declaring variables or parameters
 ğŸ”¸ They help in automatically matching the datatype of a variable with a table column
 ğŸ”¸ This makes the code more flexible and maintainable
 ğŸ”¸ Types of Variable Attributes:
      PL/SQL supports two types of variable attributes:
     ğŸ”¸  %TYPE
     ğŸ”¸ %ROWTYPE

1ï¸âƒ£ %TYPE Attribute

ğŸ”¸ Column-level attributes allow us to declare a variable with the same data type as a column in a database table.
ğŸ”¸ This is useful when we want to ensure that the variable matches the column's datatype exactly.
ğŸ”¸ It is done using the %TYPE attribute.

âœ… Key Points:
   ğŸ”¸  %TYPE is used to copy the datatype of a specific column.
   ğŸ”¸  Helps avoid datatype mismatch errors.

ğŸ“Œ Syntax:

   	Variable_Name Table_Name.Column_Name%TYPE;

EXAMPLE:

 WRITE A PL/SQL PROGRAM TO DISPLAY THE NAME AND SALRY OF THE EMPLOYEES IF THE EMPNO IS 7369.

DECLARE 
   V_NAME EMP.ENAME%TYPE ;
   V_SAL EMP.SAL%TYPE ;
BEGIN 
    SELECT ENAME ,SAL INTO V_NAME ,V_SAL 
    FROM EMP 
    WHERE EMPNO= 7369 ;
       DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(V_NAME || ' ' || V_SAL);
END ;
/

2ï¸âƒ£  %ROWTYPE Attribute

 ğŸ”¸ A rowâ€‘level attribute declares a record variable that can hold an entire row fetched from a table
 ğŸ”¸ It is specified using the %ROWTYPE attribute.

ğŸ“Œ Syntax:

    variable_name table_name%ROWTYPE;

EXAMPLE :

Write a pl/sql programm to display name ,job and salary of the employe get the values from user as empno.

DECLARE 
    I EMP%ROWTYPE ;
BEGIN 
   SELECT ENAME,JOB,SAL INTO I.ENAME ,I.JOB,I.SAL
   FROM EMP 
   WHERE EMPNO=&NO ;
     DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(I.ENAME || ' ' || I.JOB ||' '  || I.SAL);
END ;
/

Write a pl/sql programm to display name ,job and salary of the employe get the values from user as empno.
EXAMPLE :
DECLARE 
    I EMP%ROWTYPE ;
BEGIN 
    SELECT * INTO I
    FROM EMP 
    WHERE EMPNO=&NO ;
      DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(I.ENAME || ' ' || I.JOB ||' '  || I.SAL);
END ;
/


